100% REGENERATED

Panini, publishers of Doctor Who Magazine have acquired the licence for Doctor Who Adventures. The first regenerated issue went on sale 23rd April 2015!

Doctor Who Adventures changed its look and has aged-up in profile, to appeal to readers of all ages from 5-500!

Doctor Who Adventures, is officially licensed by the BBC and features 100% original material, celebrating all of Doctor Who.

Doctor Who is the world's longest running science-fiction series and was first shown on British television in 1963. In 2005 the series was reinvented and relaunched for the twenty-first century and became an overnight ratings success in the UK. Shown in America and Canada, the popularity of the series in North America is on the increase!

description:
Proper Japanese Title: マーガレット

Margaret is Shueisha's second oldest ongoing manga magazine. Launched in 1963, though Ribon (also a shojo manga magazine) is older, Margaret has become the largest shojo manga franchise at Shueisha. While Ribon was always a monthly, Margaret began as a weekly (years before Shueisha had a shonen weekly) and was able to feature long-running titles like Ace o Nerae! (one of the all-time most popular shojo manga franchises).

Within a year it also gained its first spin-off magazine, Bessatsu Margaret, a monthly which has now lasted over fifty years. It also had other spin-offs, such as The Margaret (more oriented for one-shots) and though the magazine slowed to a biweekly publishing rate in 1988 (which it continues today), it remains the most frequent shojo magazine at Shueisha and one of the few current shojo magazines that publishes more than once a month.

Proper Japanese Title: 別冊マーガレット

Bessatsu Margaret began as a monthly spin-off of Margaret, the year after Margaret was established, but with both of them lasting continously for over fifty years, Bessatsu has firmly established itself as its own franchise within the Margaret Comics brand and over the decades has published some of the best-known and popular works under the label. It is intended for a slightly older female audience than Margaret, though both are considered shojo magazines.

Bessatsu Margaret has had some special issue spin-offs of its own (like Bianca) but it's most successful was Deluxe Margaret which ran from 1967-2010. After its end, the new magazine Bessatsu Margaret: Sister was launched which is published irregularly and the current special issue magazine of Bessatsu Margaret.

description:
Proper Japanese Title: クッキー

Cookie started out as a special issue of Ribon in 1999, but was more specifically, a rebranding of the then-current magazine Bouquet. Bouquet ended in 2000, and its editorial department shifted over to Cookie which became an independent magazine and began publishing at a monthly rate later that year. Considered a revival at the attempt of reaching out to teenage girl (as Ribon Teens had tried a few years earlier), the material is sometimes considered shojo and other times josei due to the fact the targeted audience is older than Ribon (shojo) but younger than Cocohana (josei).

Since 2012, the magazine has slowed to a bimonthly numbering rate though it still kept the numbering the same, so even numbers for the bimonthly years do not exist. For example, in 2015, the six issues released were 1, 3, 5, 7, 9 and 11. When it was still a monthly magazine, Cookie had its own special issue, Cookie Box, which was published quarterly.

Proper Japanese Title: グランドジャンプ

Grand Jump was a merging of Business Jump and Super Jump into a new magazine, in an effort to stay with the changing seinen manga market. Though it took over some of the more popular serials, initially most of the ongoing works were published through sister magazine, Grand Jump Premium.

Though the magazine comes out twice a month, not every serial in it is published at this rate with a number of them being monthly or even more irregular. Somewhat uniquely, the magazine's contents are mostly dominated by sequels and spin-offs to popular franchises from other magazines. Outside of Super Jump and Business Jump, it is the home to spin-offs of Innocent and Terra Formars (from Weekly Young Jump) and spin-offs of Captain Tsubasa and Jigoku Sensei Nūbē (from Weekly Shonen Jump).

You began in 1980 as a special issue of Monthly Seventeen (a more fashion-oriented magazine), becoming its own proper magazine in 1982. Aimed at the josei (young adult women) demographic, which was still fairly new in manga at the time, You was soon followed by a number of spin-off magazines in the 80's, the most successful of the two being Young You and Office You.

Though it started out as a monthly and is one today, from 1993-2011, the magazine was released twice a month. It's also had its works published under a number of different brands over the decades such as You Comics or Queen's Comics and now, Margaret Comics.

Hobby's Jump, spun out of Monthly Shonen Jump, was something of a precursor to V Jump. An early attempt at blending video game and manga magazines together, it lasted from 1983-1988 for sixteen issues (publishing irregularly).

description:
Proper Japanese Title: ヤングユー

Young You was a josei manga magazine that launched in 1986, starting out for a few months as a special issue of Monthly Seventeen (Seventeen being a fashion magazine that occasionally ran comics). After a few months it officially launched as its own monthly magazine and a label for its own serialized manga was created, Young You Comics.

Though the title of the magazine references the naming conventions of things like Jump/Young Jump, both You and Young You are considered to be aimed at an adult female audience and when Young You was cancelled in 2005, some of its serializations transferred to You while some went to Chorus (the other josei magazine from Shueisha).

Serials from this magazine include:

  • Dandy to Watashi
  • Do Da Dancin'!
  • Double House
  • Pietà
